00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:14.100
Welcome to the Library of Congress
on this 72nd Anniversary of D-Day.

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:17.870
Today's program was inspired
by Michael Grant's recent book,

00:05:17.870 --> 00:05:20.190
Front Lines, and it gives
us an opportunity to talk

00:05:20.190 --> 00:05:25.800
about imagined roles of women in
the military during World War II

00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:29.490
and also gives us an opportunity to
compare the events of World War II

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.940
with 21st century military life.

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:37.600 position:56%
Now, Front Lines the book is the
first in a planned trilogy of books.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:40.180
Mr. Grant is also the
author of the Gone series

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:42.170
and the Magnificent Twelve series

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:45.020
and he spent much of
his life on the move.

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:49.110
He was raised in a miliary
family and as I understand it,

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:53.320
spent his years in 13 different
schools in five different states

00:05:53.320 --> 00:05:57.100
and Europe so quite a
lot of moving around.

00:05:57.100 --> 00:06:00.570
His Front Lines book
imagines a World War II

00:06:00.570 --> 00:06:04.120
with enlisted service
members of both genders

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:09.160 position:56%
and it specifically chronicles three
young women of diverse backgrounds

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:12.850
who are placed in combat alongside
of their male counterparts

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:14.150
so Michael, thank you very much

00:06:14.150 --> 00:06:16.820
for joining us today
to discuss your book.

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:20.120
I want to introduce the other
guests but before I do that,

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:23.310
I want to ask you to read a
short passage from Front Lines

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:27.320
so that we can set the stage
for today's discussion.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:28.970
&gt;&gt; Should we do that now?

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:30.270
&gt;&gt; Yup, cool.

00:06:30.270 --> 00:06:31.570
You can sit there.

00:06:31.570 --> 00:06:34.450
&gt;&gt; Oh excellent, so much easier.

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:36.860
I'll just stretch out here.

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:41.370 position:56%
I've chosen a passage that's only I
think about 78 pages long [laughter]

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:45.640
so it shouldn't be a problem.

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:48.490
Where we are right now is that one

00:06:48.490 --> 00:06:51.810
of our main characters
Rio has been dragged along

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:55.490
on a mission that's not going to go
very well but it involves a landing

00:06:55.490 --> 00:07:01.110
on a beach and this is her first
time in any kind of serious trouble

00:07:01.110 --> 00:07:03.670
and they're jumping off
the boat right then.

00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:04.970
"Rio lurches to her right.

00:07:04.970 --> 00:07:07.780
Three steps, four, five, ten,
fifteen, counting them off,

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:10.450
drops to her knees, plants the
butt of her rifle and lies face

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:12.390
down on her belly with the
weapon pointing towards

00:07:12.390 --> 00:07:15.480
where she thinks the
machine gunner might be.

00:07:15.480 --> 00:07:17.490
Fifteen hundred rounds per minute,

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:20.090
the standard German machine gun
fires fifteen hundred rounds

00:07:20.090 --> 00:07:21.390
per minute.

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:24.520
The machine gun opens up again,
loud but distant followed by softer

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:28.520
but way too near pff pff
sounds as the bullets hit sand.

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:31.060
Soft whimpering noises are
coming from her throat,

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:33.750
unlike any sound she's
ever made before.

00:07:33.750 --> 00:07:35.920
A split second slower than
Rio had hit the ground,

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:37.260
Kerwin [phonetic] cries out.

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.140
He says, "Oh."

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:41.060
Just that, "Oh."

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:42.800
Rio sees him fall backwards.

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:44.100
His head lands in the edge

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.440
of retreating foam,
legs folded beneath him.

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:47.890
"Castle, you hit?"

00:07:47.890 --> 00:07:49.190
No answer.

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:50.490
"God no, God no, God no."

00:07:50.490 --> 00:07:52.560
The Jeep roars and splashes
out of the landing craft

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.710
and instantly draws the fire
of the enemy machine gun.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:57.010
"Are you hit?

00:07:57.010 --> 00:07:58.310
Castle, are you hit?"

00:07:58.310 --> 00:07:59.610
"Doc? Doc?"

00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:00.910
someone yells.

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:03.740 position:56%
The Jeep swerves left and goes nose
down in a hole, rear wheels spinning

00:08:03.740 --> 00:08:05.770
and throwing up a plume of sand.

00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:08.820
"Richlin, give doc a hand with
Castle", Sergeant Cole yells.

00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:11.210
"Stick, get that BAR up
onto that dune there.

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:12.520
Put some fire on that machine gun.

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:13.820
Take gear with you.

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:16.680 position:56%
Castain, Pang, Suarez [assumed
spellings], stay low and follow me."

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:19.610
Rio crawls towards her stricken
comrade, elbows digging,

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:21.980
knees pushing, heart gone mad.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:25.390 position:56%
The doc who came to shore with
fourth squad is hunched over Castle.

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:28.010
He grabs at something in his
medical kit and now Rio sees

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:30.630
that Castle is flailing
spasmodically,

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:33.250
arms and legs jerking,
torso heaving.

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:36.020
An advancing wave covers
his face and foam.

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:38.010
"Pull him back, pull him back,
pull him back God damn it!

00:08:38.010 --> 00:08:41.060
He'll drown" the medic shouts.

00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:43.730
Rio grabs Castles legs and
has to rise to her own knees

00:08:43.730 --> 00:08:45.030
in order to get leverage.

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:48.480
She is acutely aware of her exposed
back but hauls him out of the surf.

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.440
"Hold him down" the medic
says through gritted teeth,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:53.190
as he tears open a bandage.

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:54.560 position:56%
"Gotta stop the bleeding, his neck."

00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:58.000
"Take it easy Castle,
take it easy" Rio says.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.190
Blood pulses from Castle's throat

00:09:00.190 --> 00:09:02.000
like a garden hose
someone is kinking

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.150
and releasing, kinking
and releasing.

00:09:04.150 --> 00:09:06.790
The blood looks like chocolate
syrup in the darkness.

00:09:06.790 --> 00:09:08.250
Kerwin is making guttural sounds,

00:09:08.250 --> 00:09:10.670
words full of urgency
with no vowels.

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:15.040
Rio rises again just high enough to
place her hands on Kerwin's chest

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:18.700
and hold him down but as she does
this she feels slippery warmth

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:20.190
and realizes that large quantities

00:09:20.190 --> 00:09:22.560
of blood are gushing
from his upper chest.

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:24.790
He's been hit twice, not once.

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:26.090
"Gotta take it easy, Castle.

00:09:26.090 --> 00:09:27.390
Let doc work."

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:30.280
It wound sound better if my
teeth weren't chattering,

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:31.810
but Kerwin isn't hearing her.

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:34.110
He jerks wildly, tries to
say something that comes

00:09:34.110 --> 00:09:37.660
out as a plaintive grunt,
then lays back down quieting.

00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:39.900
Doc slaps a pressure
bandage on but the artery

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:41.720
in Castle's neck has barely slowed.

00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:45.350
It's like trying to block a
fire hydrant with your fingers.

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:47.170 position:56%
Doc rips Castle's uniform shirt open

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:50.910
and there's a second hole
near, too near to his heart.

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:53.200
The medic curses and then
covers that by telling Castle,

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:54.500
"It's okay, it's okay soldier.

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:55.800
You'll be okay.

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:57.730
Going home is all, going home."

00:09:57.730 --> 00:10:00.650
It's a lie, but Kerwin
never hears it anyway.

00:10:00.650 --> 00:10:02.460
Rio feels his heart stop.

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:05.830
One second there's a wild beating
thing in his chest, then nothing.

00:10:05.830 --> 00:10:09.740
Kerwin's last breath was a
slow, wet, wheeze of exhalation

00:10:09.740 --> 00:10:12.400
as if he's sinking back into
an easy chair after a long day.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:15.960
The machine gun shatters
and digs divots pff pff pff

00:10:15.960 --> 00:10:18.680
in the sand near Rio so she has
to roll away clutching her rifle

00:10:18.680 --> 00:10:21.000
to her chest with blood
slicked hands.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
Kerwin is dead without ever
getting a chance to speak.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:29.510
His final intelligible word was
just that single syllable, "Oh."

00:10:29.510 --> 00:10:38.040
[ Applause ]

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:39.340
&gt;&gt; So that was cheerful [laughter].

00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:43.500
&gt;&gt; Well thank you for that
very descriptive reading,

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:45.260
thank you so much.

