How many people in the
audience are a family

00:14:46.310 --> 00:14:50.740
who is connected to the military?

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:53.720
Wow! A lot of you.

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:57.080
Great, so this is perfect
[laughter].

00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:05.550
Today, we have two really special
women here because if you think

00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:13.070
about it, how many, I guess kids
actually have their moms deployed?

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:19.440
It's hard to see because
the lights are in our eyes

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:23.380
so nobody really has a mom
deployed well, some of the moms

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:28.400
that I've met have told me really
if you think about all of you think

00:15:28.400 --> 00:15:34.130
about your mom being deployed and
what you would kind of miss right?

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:38.820
Because the moms tell me, the moms
who are in the military service,

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:41.720
they tell me how hard it
is for them to be away

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:47.860
on those special occasions like
when their son or daughter is going

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:49.950
to college, or they
missed their graduation,

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:53.960
their high school graduation or
being there for special birthdays

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:56.600
or all kinds of special events.

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:00.860
So, if you think about that event
and not having your mom there

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:06.370
and having your mom in Iraq or
Afghanistan it's kind of hard

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:08.490
so you can see it from
both points of view.

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:11.090
You can see how the moms
are missing their children

00:16:11.090 --> 00:16:16.960 position:56%
and the children are missing their
mothers so this is truly a sacrifice

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:23.990 position:56%
that I think female military leaders
make when they join the service.

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:28.000
Has anyone here in the
audience, has anyone thought

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.800
about joining the military?

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:37.200
Okay, a couple, all right.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:42.960
As you've meet Kristen
and you've met Jessica-

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:44.260
&gt;&gt; Rebecca.

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:45.560
&gt;&gt; Rebecca-

00:16:45.560 --> 00:16:48.730
&gt;&gt; I'll be Jessica
for you thought ma'am.

00:16:48.730 --> 00:16:52.960
&gt;&gt; Okay [laughter], I'm
sorry so I'd like for them

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:56.940
to tell you their stories and
why they went into the military,

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:58.530
and what kind of jobs they do,

00:16:58.530 --> 00:17:04.190
and you'll see really how
special they are so Kristen,

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:05.490
do you want to start with yours?

00:17:05.490 --> 00:17:08.030
&gt;&gt; Sure, hi everybody, I'm Kristen.

00:17:08.030 --> 00:17:11.800 position:56%
I grew up in Weymouth, Massachusetts
which is about 30 minutes south

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:15.840
of Boston and for as
long as I can remember,

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:17.850
I grew up wanting to
be an astronaut.

00:17:17.850 --> 00:17:19.850
I was upset when I
went to kindergarten

00:17:19.850 --> 00:17:21.920
because I could not
watch shuttle launches

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:25.720
so my poor parents thought
I would grow out of it

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:28.070
and I never did, to their dismay.

00:17:28.070 --> 00:17:31.470
But when I grew up I was like
well, I have to join the Air Force,

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:34.770
that's what astronauts
did and come to find

00:17:34.770 --> 00:17:38.840
out the Naval Academy has the most
astronaut graduates in the country

00:17:38.840 --> 00:17:42.390
so I was very binary and I was
like well, I'm going there.

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:46.180
And dad drove me down to Annapolis
and I was totally smitten.

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:49.280
I loved everything about it
and my mom was totally dismayed

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:52.290
when I came back and realized I
wasn't going to change my mind

00:17:52.290 --> 00:17:56.660
so went to Navy, had an awesome
time there, played soccer,

00:17:56.660 --> 00:17:59.810
studied aerospace engineering.

00:17:59.810 --> 00:18:04.120
When I graduated, I was lucky
enough to select aviation,

00:18:04.120 --> 00:18:07.340
went to flight school down
in Pensacola and Meridian

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:10.990
and was lucky enough to get
F18s out of flight school.

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:14.160
I got sent over to
Lemoore, California which is

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:18.390 position:56%
about 45 minutes south of Fresno and
I have somehow managed to live there

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:21.820
for just over a decade now,
which is probably a world record

00:18:21.820 --> 00:18:23.650 position:56%
in the military, not having to move.

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:26.200
I've done three operational
tours over there

00:18:26.200 --> 00:18:30.320
and an instructor tour
and had a fabulous time.

00:18:30.320 --> 00:18:31.990
As they said, I've
done a couple of trips

00:18:31.990 --> 00:18:34.930 position:56%
over to the Gulf and to Afghanistan.

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:38.120
We actually just got home a year
ago with my current squadron

00:18:38.120 --> 00:18:40.630
so it's been a fabulous
experience for me.

00:18:40.630 --> 00:18:45.460 position:56%
The people have been outstanding and
I get a somewhat expensive aircraft

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:48.200
to fly around on the
government's dime so thanks

00:18:48.200 --> 00:18:52.510
to all the taxpayers [laughter],
I really appreciate it.

