00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:04.480
that you've done and the
career path that you've chosen.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:08.270
So will you be deployed again?

00:19:08.270 --> 00:19:09.570
&gt;&gt; Probably.

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:12.990
I think I probably have about one
more operational tour so I'm going

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:16.300
to an instructional tour for about
two and a half years in November

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:20.100
and then rotate out of
there and go back to sea

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:24.330
for about a 30 month tour and then
I'll be right about the time I have

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:27.940
to decide if I want to get
out or stay in so we'll see.

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:31.330
I have at least seven more years
before I have to grow up I guess.

00:19:31.330 --> 00:19:34.390
&gt;&gt; All right, Rebecca, do you
want to tell us your story?

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:38.390
&gt;&gt; Sure, I'm originally
from Chicago, Illinois.

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:40.060
Anybody from Chicago in here?

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:41.450
Probably not.

00:19:41.450 --> 00:19:42.750
&gt;&gt; Wait a minute, one person.

00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.360
It's hard to see.

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:48.840
&gt;&gt; So, when I was a kid I
actually wanted to be a filmmaker.

00:19:48.840 --> 00:19:53.560
I went in to watch a film called
Annie, and I left and told my mom,

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:55.730
" I want to be Annie" and she
said, "Well, you have parents,

00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:59.670
you cannot be an orphan"
[laughter] and so I realized

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:02.740
that I wanted to make films.

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:06.030
And so, I went to school and
studied television production

00:20:06.030 --> 00:20:10.490
and I was a senior in college
going that route when 9/11 happened

00:20:10.490 --> 00:20:14.440
and for me, I just really
wanted to serve and give back

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:17.040
so I joined the Army,
which is the best branch

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:18.410
in case you don't know [laughter].

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:22.430
&gt;&gt; How many years have
we won in football?

00:20:22.430 --> 00:20:28.200
&gt;&gt; I know, I know, not a good
football team but a fun branch.

00:20:28.200 --> 00:20:33.600
So when I was in, at the time
my civilian job was working

00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:36.210
in sports production so
I was working for ESPN

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:41.110
and Comcast doing some really
cool, fun things with the Yankees,

00:20:41.110 --> 00:20:44.950
and when I deployed the Army
found out and they were like well,

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:46.740
you're going to tell
soldier stories now

00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:50.960
so it was an incredible experience
because I spent about three years

00:20:50.960 --> 00:20:55.400
between Iraq, Afghanistan,
and Kuwait traveling around

00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:58.400
and interviewing soldiers
and videotaping them

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:04.900 position:56%
and basically telling the American
public what these men and women did.

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:12.100
And in 2011, at that time I was one
of the first women to get attached

00:21:12.100 --> 00:21:16.960
to Navy Seals and Special
Forces and Navy Seals (Navy)

00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:21.860
in case you don't know, are some
of the most awesome folks out there

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:24.170
and Special Forces as well.

00:21:24.170 --> 00:21:27.270
And women, at the time
of Afghanistan,

00:21:27.270 --> 00:21:28.570
nobody had talked to them.

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:32.280
Nobody knew what they were
doing or how they were working

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:35.270
so what they did is they took a
bunch of women in the military,

00:21:35.270 --> 00:21:39.230
they put them with the Navy Seals
and basically our job was to go out

00:21:39.230 --> 00:21:41.090
and talk to these women,
and talk to children,

00:21:41.090 --> 00:21:45.420
and find out what they were doing
because as most people know,

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:49.230
the status that women have in a
country is directly correlated

00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:51.940
on how well that country
does economically,

00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:56.530
how well it does socially, so
that was a big part of what I did.

00:21:56.530 --> 00:21:59.290
And while I was over there, I
remember I was in the middle

00:21:59.290 --> 00:22:02.230
of Afghanistan and a buddy of
mine said to me, "You know,

00:22:02.230 --> 00:22:03.530
if you could do one
thing for the rest

00:22:03.530 --> 00:22:04.830
of your life what would that be?"

00:22:04.830 --> 00:22:09.050
And I said, "I want to make
films" and that's what I did.

00:22:09.050 --> 00:22:13.500
He said you survived two years
in the middle of a war zone,

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:15.710
how hard can being a filmmaker be?

00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:20.510
He had obviously never been to
Hollywood [laughter] so I went

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:24.670
to Los Angeles and spent the
last three years making films

00:22:24.670 --> 00:22:28.780
and I'm finishing up a short
film that is going to be

00:22:28.780 --> 00:22:31.960
on HBO probably next
fall, which is really cool

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:34.620
and it's basically telling
stories about that film

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:37.500
about a wounded warrior
who comes back

00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:40.260
and so I realized my calling
now is really telling some

00:22:40.260 --> 00:22:41.560
of those stories.

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:42.860
&gt;&gt; Congratulations.

00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:44.160
&gt;&gt; What's the title?

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:45.500
&gt;&gt; It's called, One Halloween,
which is a very short film

00:22:45.500 --> 00:22:49.660
about 15 minutes but we had 25
Veterans come and work on the set

00:22:49.660 --> 00:22:52.270 position:56%
and a couple Vets here actually
supporting me that were on that set.

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:54.070
I've got to give a
shout out to them.

00:22:54.070 --> 00:22:59.720
[ Applause ]

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:01.020
&gt;&gt; Hi, welcome.

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.890
&gt;&gt; And it's great because as you
know, when you serve and you're

00:23:03.890 --> 00:23:06.270
in the military, you're part
of a family and when you leave,

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:10.510
